        whichToChoose: {
          id: 'which-to-choose',
          title: 'Which One-Click Installer Should You Choose?',
          content: '**The right installer depends on your workflow: Ollama for developers, LM Studio for GUI users, Jan AI for privacy, GPT4All for simplicity.**',
          items: [
            'вң… **Compliance note**: For regulated industries (healthcare, finance, legal), Jan AI or Ollama are recommended вҖ” both MIT-licensed, no telemetry, fully auditable codebase.',
            '**Choose Ollama** if you are a developer who wants to script, automate, or integrate local models into applications. See [How to Install Ollama](/local-llms/how-to-install-ollama) for setup.',
            '**Choose LM Studio** if you prefer a polished desktop GUI and want access to the full range of Hugging Face GGUF models. See [How to Install LM Studio](/local-llms/how-to-install-lm-studio) for setup.',
            '**Choose Jan AI** if data privacy is your highest priority вҖ” no telemetry, fully offline, fully open source.',
            '**Choose GPT4All** if you want the simplest possible experience with no terminal commands, or if you want built-in document chat (LocalDocs) without additional configuration.',
            'As of April 2026, all four tools can coexist on the same machine вҖ” they use different default ports (11434, 1234, 1337, 4891) and separate model storage directories. Models in GGUF format can be shared between them.',
            'рҹ“Ң **In Plain Terms**: Think of these tools like app stores for AI models вҖ” they handle the installation, storage, and running of models so you never touch a command line (unless you want to).',
          ],
        },
        regionalContext: {
          id: 'regional-context',
          title: 'Which Regions Regulate One-Click LLM Installers?',
          content: [
            '**EU / GDPR:** All four tools run inference entirely on-device вҖ” no prompt text, context, or output is transmitted to external servers during inference. For EU professionals processing personal data under GDPR, the ranking by compliance strength is: (1) Jan AI вҖ” fully open-source MIT, no telemetry, fully auditable; (2) Ollama вҖ” open-source MIT, confirmed no telemetry, localhost-only API by default; (3) GPT4All вҖ” open-source, opt-in only telemetry, LocalDocs processes documents fully offline; (4) LM Studio вҖ” closed-source, anonymous analytics enabled by default (disable: Settings вҶ’ Privacy вҶ’ Send anonymous usage data вҶ’ off). For German BSI guideline compliance, Jan AI or Ollama are the recommended choices вҖ” both provide a fully auditable open-source inference stack.',
            '**Japan (METI):** METI AI Governance Guidelines require documenting where AI inference occurs. All four tools run inference locally and store model files at documented paths: Ollama at `~/.ollama/models/`, LM Studio at `~/Library/Application Support/LM Studio/` on macOS, Jan AI at `~/jan/models/`, GPT4All at `~/Library/Application Support/nomic.ai/GPT4All/` on macOS. These paths can be included in AI governance documentation. Japanese enterprise teams typically prefer Jan AI or Ollama for open-source auditability and METI traceability requirements.',
            '**China:** All four tools support Qwen2.5 models вҖ” the primary local LLM choice for Chinese enterprises. In Ollama: `ollama pull qwen2.5:7b`. In LM Studio and Jan AI: search "qwen2.5" in the model browser. In GPT4All: Qwen2.5 models are available under the Qwen category in the model library. Under China\'s Data Security Law (ж•°жҚ®е®үе…Ёжі•), local inference via any of these tools satisfies data localization requirements вҖ” all processing stays on-device with no external API calls during inference.',
            'рҹ’Ў **Governance tip**: Document which tool you use and its model storage path in your AI governance log. METI and EU AI Act both require inference location documentation for enterprise deployments.',
          ],
        },
        commonMistakes: {
          id: 'common-mistakes',
          title: 'What Are Common Mistakes When Choosing a Local LLM Installer?',
          items: [
            '**Installing all four tools and running them simultaneously:** All four tools use port ranges that can conflict (11434, 1234, 1337, 4891). Running multiple tools at once causes port conflicts and wastes RAM loading multiple inference engines. Pick one tool as your primary and only start others when needed.',
            '**Choosing LM Studio without disabling telemetry:** LM Studio collects anonymous usage analytics by default. For privacy-sensitive use, disable immediately: Settings вҶ’ Privacy вҶ’ Send anonymous usage data вҶ’ off. Jan AI and Ollama collect no telemetry by default вҖ” no action needed.',
            '**Using GPT4All for API integration:** GPT4All\'s optional API server works but is less reliable and less documented than Ollama\'s. For any application that calls a local LLM via API, use Ollama (localhost:11434). GPT4All is best kept as a chat interface only.',
            '**Downloading models separately for each tool:** All four tools use GGUF format. A model downloaded for one tool can be reused by the others вҖ” you do not need separate copies. In Ollama, point to a local GGUF file with `ollama create`. In LM Studio and Jan AI, browse to the file in the model management screen.',
            '**Expecting Jan AI\'s extension system to be production-grade:** Jan AI\'s plugin and extension system is designed for experimentation, not production workloads. For production RAG, build a dedicated pipeline with Ollama and a vector database.',
          ],
        },
