        commonMistakes: {
          title: 'Common Mistakes When Running Local LLMs on a Laptop',
          items: [
            '**Loading a 7B model on 8 GB RAM without closing other apps:** A 7B model at Q4_K_M uses ~4.5 GB. macOS or Windows typically use 3вҖ“4 GB of RAM themselves. On an 8 GB machine, loading a 7B model with a browser and multiple tabs open causes memory pressure, swap usage, and speeds as low as 2вҖ“5 tok/sec. Close the browser and unnecessary apps before loading models above 3B on 8 GB RAM laptops.',
            '**Using Q8_0 on a laptop when Q4_K_M is sufficient:** Q8_0 doubles the RAM requirement vs Q4_K_M with negligible quality gain for most conversational tasks. On a laptop with limited RAM and higher thermal load, Q4_K_M is always the better choice unless you have 32+ GB and are running the model on GPU.',
            '**Running long generation sessions without a stand:** Sustained inference for 20+ minutes on a flat desk causes thermal throttling on most laptops within 15 minutes. A $15 laptop stand that raises the base by 2вҖ“3 cm extends throttle-free runtime from 10 to 20+ minutes without any other changes.',
            '**Expecting laptop speeds to match cloud API speeds:** GPT-4o via API produces 80вҖ“150 tok/sec. A 7B model on an 8 GB laptop produces 10вҖ“25 tok/sec on CPU. This is a 4вҖ“15Г— speed difference. For interactive use, laptop inference is fine. For batch processing large documents, cloud APIs are faster and cheaper at low volume.',
            '**Picking model size based on parameter count rather than RAM fit:** A 13B model sounds better than a 7B model вҖ” but on a 16 GB laptop with a browser running, the 13B at Q4_K_M barely fits. The 7B at Q5_K_M (higher quality quantization) runs faster and often produces better results than a 13B at Q4_K_M fighting for memory.',
          ],
        },
